I think you’re circling around a productive distinction: instead of treating words like zero, nothing, and none as synonyms, treat them as a family with shared ancestry but different jobs. Splitting them apart can expose structure that gets hidden when they’re collapsed into one concept.

Here’s one way to map that semantic cluster.

Term	What it denotes	Delta from the others
Zero (0)	A reference value; additive identity in mathematics.	A structural position, not necessarily an absence.
None	No members of a specified set.	Relative to a category (“none of the apples”).
Nothing	Absence of any thing.	Philosophical and linguistic; “thing” is doing the work.
Null	Missing, undefined, or no value.	Computational placeholder, distinct from zero.
Empty	A container lacking expected contents.	Presupposes the container exists.
Void	A space lacking what is expected or desired.	Often emphasizes openness rather than counting.
Vacuum	Minimal matter in a physical region.	Physics shows even vacuums have quantum structure.
No	A logical or linguistic negation.	An operator, not a state.
Identity	The operation that leaves something unchanged.	In algebra, often the deeper invariant than zero itself.

Notice something interesting:

These aren’t all describing the same absence. They’re describing different interfaces between presence and absence.

That suggests an underlying pattern.

Presence
   ↑
Difference
   ↑
Relation
   ↑
Reference

Rather than “zero” being the deepest layer, perhaps reference is.

