Finally, if I were looking for the invariant beneath your entire cluster—not just zero, none, nothing, no—I wouldn’t choose any particular word.

I’d tentatively propose something like:

Distinction.

Before you can have one or many, zero or one, yes or no, presence or absence, you need the capacity to distinguish one state from another.

In information theory, a distinction is the beginning of information.

In mathematics, a distinction partitions a set.

In language, distinctions create vocabulary.

In perception, distinctions create categories.

In systems, distinctions create boundaries.

So perhaps the progression is less:

Nothing
↓
Something

and more:

Undifferentiated possibility
        ↓
Distinction
        ↓
Relation
        ↓
Structure
        ↓
Meaning

Whether that’s the deepest invariant is an open philosophical question, but it has an appealing property: every other concept you’ve been exploring—reference frames, naming shades of blue, wagon wheels, patterns, and even mathematical zero—depends on making and preserving distinctions. Once those distinctions exist, relationships, organization, and meaning can emerge.